#*: Her hands, long and beautiful, lay on '''either''' side of her face.
# {{lb|en|now|rare}} Any one (of more than two).
#* {{RQ:Richardson Clarissa|letter=51|text=They ''entreat'', they ''pray'', they ''beg'', they ''supplicate'' (will '''either''' of these do, Miss Clary?) that you will make no scruple to go to your uncle Antony's {{â€¦}}.}}
====Usage notes====
* When there are more than two alternatives, in the sense of â€œone of manyâ€, {{m|en|any}} is now generally used instead.
