===Pronoun===
{{en-pron}}
# One or the other of two people or things.
#: {{ux|en|He made me two offers, but I did not accept '''either'''.}}
#* {{quote-web|en|date=7 September 2013|author=Daniel Taylor|title=Danny Welbeck leads England's rout of Moldova but hit by Ukraine ban|work=The Guardian|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2013/sep/06/england-moldova-world-cup-qualifier-matchreport|passage={{w|Roy Hodgson|Hodgson}} may now have to bring in {{w|James Milner}} on the left and, on that basis, a certain amount of gloss was taken off a night on which {{w|Danny Welbeck|Welbeck}} scored twice but barely celebrated '''either''' before leaving the pitch angrily complaining to the Slovakian referee.}}
# {{lb|en|obsolete}} [[both|Both]], each of two or more.
#* {{RQ:Bacon War with Spain|passage=Scarce a palm of ground could be gotten by '''either''' of the three.}}
#* {{RQ:Spenser Faerie Queene|book=III|canto=I|passage=And '''either''' vowd with all their power and wit, / To let not others honour be defaste {{...}}}}
#* '''1872''', {{w|Oliver Wendell Holmes, Sr.}}, ''The Poet at the Breakfast-Table''
#*: There have been three famous talkers in Great British, '''either''' of whom would illustrate what I say about dogmatists.
===Adverb===
{{en-adv|-}}
# {{lb|en|conjunctive|after a negative}} As well.
#: {{ux|en|I don't like him, and I don't like her '''either'''.}}
#: {{ux|en|I know a cheap Spanish restaurant. It's not far from here, '''either'''.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|year=1959|author={{w|Georgette Heyer}}|title={{w|The Unknown Ajax}}|chapter=1|passage=But Richmond{{...}}appeared to lose himself in his own reflections. Some pickled crab, which he had not touched, had been removed with a damson pie; and his sister saw{{...}}that he had eaten no more than a spoonful of that '''either'''.}}
====Usage notes====
After a positive statement, {{m|en|too}} is commonly used: â€œI like him, and I like her too.â€
{{m|en|either|Either}} is sometimes used, especially in North American English, where {{m|en|neither}} would be more traditionally accurate: â€œIâ€™m not hungry.â€ â€œMe either.â€
